(180, 'Under Construction\nAug 25,2011 at 7:00am by Mike \nMike, and his wife Mary knew even before they got married 12 years ago that they wanted a big family. After trying to get pregnant for over a year, the couple began investigating international vs. national adoptions and decided to explore both options.\nMike comes from a very special adoption background in that his parents took in adopted his brother so Mike grew up, sharing meals, playtime and love in their home.\nAfter briefly exploring an international adoption and realizing the wait could be nearly four years for a healthy newborn, the Florida couple shifted gears and began filling out paperwork for a domestic adoption.\nThey were interested in newborns. “We decided to try the domestic route, so my home study agency recommended a local agency to initiate a domestic newborn adoption with a birth mother,” says Mike today. “We were open to sibling groups too.”\n“I come from a family of foster children and my parents took in dozens of  kids over the course of our childhood, and we received many priceless and amazing experiences” says Mike. “We hoped we’d get matched pretty quickly.”\nThey flew through their paperwork, parenting training classes and home study in six months. Mike also has a secret weapon in his adoption arsenal: He has a background in technology and created adoption software that pairs newborns or foster children and awaiting parents. While ParentFinder.com didn’t directly help Mike, he was a fountain of adoption knowledge and by now had adopted not once but twice..\n“We were quickly matched to birth mother in her final month of pregnancy. We spoke for hours, at least five times, and the birth mother seemed ready and eager to be through with it.  We drove north to Virginia in October,  when the baby was due, and bought the mom groceries and clothes, paid some bills for her, and she even asked Mike’s wife Mary to be present with her in the delivery room so that she could cut m', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Our story', 944, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'html', 1314201957, 0),
