(455, '<p><span style="font-size:large;font-family:arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"><strong></strong></span><span style="font-size:medium;font-family:arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"><strong>Jeremy and Kristi both grew up surrounded by the love and support of their families. They were raised in small, rural communities, where family and friends stayed close. Jeremy has one sibling and Kristi has four, but both belong to large, extended families who live nearby. Holidays, birthdays and even simple family and friend gatherings are large, noisy events where kids are the center of attention and laughter and stories (and great food) abound. </strong></span></p>\n<p><strong><span style="font-size:medium;font-family:arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">Jeremy grew up in a tiny logging community. Kristi grew up on a farm. Jeremy worked weekends and summers on his family''s farm which was just over the hill from the farm where Kristi was raised. In this environment both developed deep family values and strong work ethics. After completing high school and college, Jeremy went to work in the construction industry and Kristi began a career in the dental field. </span></strong></p>\n<p><strong><span style="font-size:medium;font-family:arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">Although they attended the same high school, it took another decade for Jeremy and Kristi''s relationship to lead to marriage and then the start of their own family, with the adoption of their first child, a son, Tanner. He is four-and-a-half years old now and, although not sure of what it means to have a sibling, he is eager for a playmate. He particularly loves babies—he loves to hold them, to sing to them, to touch their hair or to give them a hug. He will be an awesome “Big Brother.” </span></strong></p>\n<p><strong><span style="font-size:medium;font-family:arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">After Tanner was born Jeremy and Kristi purchased property and built a home in the country, next door to Jeremy''s uncle. This is an area where everyone knows their neighbors and looks out for each other. The property is surrounded by grass fields, pasture and woods. Deer and wild turkeys are in sight almost daily. Tanner can watch sheep graze across the fence while he''s running across the lawn chasing butterflies or a ball with his dog, Sadie or chasing his cat, Minnie. The only thing missing is a brother or sister to share this with. It would be hard to find a better place to raise a family. </span></strong></p>\n<p><strong><span style="font-size:medium;font-family:arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">Both Kristi and Jeremy''s parents live nearby, providing many opportunities for snuggling up on a grandparent''s lap for a song or a tickle or a story or a kiss.  It is a two mile drive to the church or the school that Tanner and his new brother or sister will attend.</span></strong></p>\n<p><strong><span style="font-size:medium;font-family:arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">After Tanner was born, Kristi placed a picture of him on the windowsill above their kitchen sink with an inscription that read, “Dreams do come true.” Jeremy and Kristi look at that picture every day and continue to dream, knowing that dreams do come true.  Their dream is to adopt again. </span></strong></p>', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Jeremy and Kristi', 1468, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'text', 1327876695, 0),
