(655, '<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#800080;font-size:medium;">Brianna...</span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#000080;font-size:small;">Our oldest daughter, Brianna, is 16 years old.  Having been an only child for eight years before Alex was born, Brianna cherishes the opportunity to be a big sister and enjoys being a strong positive role model to her younger siblings.  Brianna loves spending time with Alex and Maya and doesn''t miss an opportunity to read a book to them, paint Maya''s nails or cook them macaroni and cheese (which, according to Maya and Alex, simply tastes better when Brianna makes it).</span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#000080;font-size:small;"> </span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#000080;font-size:small;">Brianna attends a private high school where her favorite subject is English.  She has always particularly enjoyed creative writing and her witty sense of humor comes through both in person and in her writing.  Brianna is also a talented artist being able to draw freehand, virtually anything that she sees.  </span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"> </span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#000080;font-size:small;">Despite her other talents, which are many, Brianna is most passionate about her dancing.  Brianna started dancing at 3 years old and we have not been able to stop her feet ever since (nor have we tried).  Brianna is not only a featured member in her dance school''s Classical Ballet, Tap, Jazz, Modern and Hip Hop Companies, but she also works as an instructor teaching younger dancers.  Brianna''s dancing has allowed her to perform during the half-time show of two College Football Bowl games and she has trained with many famous choreographers. </span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"> </span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#000080;font-size:small;">Brianna is thrilled about the possibility of adding a new baby to our family and can''t wait to shower love on a new sibling.  </span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><img src="http://www.parentfinder.com/media/users/fromfivetosix/IMG_1571.JPG" alt="" width="200" height="250" /><img src="http://www.parentfinder.com/media/users/fromfivetosix/IMG_0047.jpg" alt="" width="175" height="219" /><img src="http://www.parentfinder.com/media/users/fromfivetosix/IMG_1506.JPG" alt="" width="200" height="150" /></p>\n<p><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#800080;font-size:medium;">Alexander... </span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#000080;font-size:small;">Our son Alexander (Alex) is seven years old.  From the time he was born, he was the happiest baby and his personality has stayed consistent as he has grown.  One of our favorite sounds in the world, is the sound of Alex''s infectious laughter, which can be set off by just about anything.  </span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#000080;font-size:small;"> </span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#000080;font-size:small;">Alex loves school and thinks his class pets, three hermit crabs, are "awesome".  He is also proud of the fact that his class picked his favorite name "crabby-dabby-doo" for one of the hermit crabs.  Alex is becoming a great reader and has gotten so confident in his abilities, that not only does he enjoy reading to himself now, but he likes reading to Maya too, which is very sweet.</span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#000080;font-size:small;"> </span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#000080;font-size:small;">Alex also loves playing sports and plays on soccer, basketball and baseball teams during their respective seasons.  He also loves swimming both in our backyard fenced-in pool and at the lake and pool at his camp during the summer.</span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"> </span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#000080;font-size:small;">A little budding musician, Alex also takes guitar lessons and his favorite part is the end of the lesson when he works on his "rock star jump".</span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"> </span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#000080;font-size:small;">Alex is a loving brother to both of his sisters.  He would do anything for his sisters and, on many occasions, has even offered Maya his last piece of dessert (which, to a 7 year old, is more important than gold).  He also loves seeing Brianna dance and always tells her how great she was.</span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"> </span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#000080;font-size:small;">Alex is a fantastic big brother and a baby will be lucky to have such an awesome big brother.  </span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><img src="http://www.parentfinder.com/media/users/fromfivetosix/IMG_4333.jpg" alt="" width="150" height="225" />        <img src="http://www.parentfinder.com/media/users/fromfivetosix/IMG_6231.jpg" alt="" width="150" height="225" />        <img src="http://www.parentfinder.com/media/users/fromfivetosix/IMG_6561.JPG" alt="" width="200" height="133" /></p>\n<div><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#800080;font-size:medium;">Maya...  </span></div>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#000080;font-size:small;">Our five year old Maya is sweet, kind and wise beyond her years.  She watches (and comments on) everything her big brother and sister do and their positive influence is helping to make her a beautiful person on the inside and outside.  When Alex learned about the tragedy in Haiti and asked if he could donate his piggy bank savings to help the people there, Maya was only two steps behind asking if she could "help the people too".  While she may not yet fully understand why we support important causes or why Brianna volunteers her time to various charities, she is curious about what they do and by talking with her about it, she starts to understand some of the values that we believe are important, including giving back to your community and others in need.</span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"> </span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#000080;font-size:small;">Maya started morning pre-school this year and her favorite school activities are painting, singing and when the "nature lady" brings animals to the class for the kids to see.</span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"> </span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#000080;font-size:small;">Her teachers call her a "joy" and comment on how compassionate she is for the other children, even reminding the teachers when it is another child''s turn to be the line leader ( a very important position in the life of a pre-schooler).</span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"> </span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:#000080;font-size:small;">Outside of school, Maya plays soccer and takes Ballet.  She loves swimming and our monthly trips to Home Depot for their kids project workshops.  Each of our kids also spend time with their Nana and Papa in upstate New York and one of Maya''s favorite things to do up there is going on pony rides.</span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"> </span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="font-family:symbol;font-size:small;color:#000080;"><span style="font-family:tahoma, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">Maya is a fantastic little sister and she is going to be a wonderful, caring, loving big sister.</span>   </span></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><img src="http://www.parentfinder.com/media/users/fromfivetosix/IMG_4805.jpg" alt="" width="185" height="231" /><img src="http://www.parentfinder.com/media/users/fromfivetosix/IMG_6226.JPG" alt="" width="200" height="133" /><img src="http://www.parentfinder.com/media/users/fromfivetosix/IMG_5460.JPG" alt="" width="200" height="133" /></p>', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Our Children', 2532, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'text', 1357112419, 0),
(656, '     I have always known I wanted children.  It’s always been my choice, but never an option.\n     If I went to sleep this evening and woke up with a child, through adoption…I would only be able to describe the child in two words.  Unconditionally loved! \n     At the age of 9, I found out that I would be unable to have children.  This was a heavy burden to bear at such a young age, but as I’ve gotten older, the heaviness has weighed on my heart.  Through a series of routine medical tests, my sister (my only sibling) and I found out that we had developed fibrous tumors in place of where our ovaries should have been.  Both of us required surgeries to remove the tumors.  Mine were a little more dense, and a full hysterectomy was needed in order to be healthy and thrive.  My sister was able to maintain her uterus, making invitro fertilization an option for her, later in life.  After some complications, my sister was able to carry a full term baby via IVF.  Due to the toll the pregnancy took on her body, she too required a full hysterectomy, soon after the birth of my first nephew.  Since, she and her husband have adopted two children.  My sister’s journey through adoption has shown me that no matter how a child comes into my life, they have grown in my heart for my lifetime.       \n     Today, I am healthy and am anxious for motherhood.  I want to share my hobbies of baking, cake decorating, cooking, reading and my most recent…golfing, with a child.\n     During our courtship, I had to face the difficult task of telling my husband that I was unable to have children.  So often, we hear of people who have been told that they cannot have children, but then, receive the surprise of their life when they do.  For me, this would never be the case.  My infertility is certain.  And, I thought could be a “deal breaker” when dating.  Luckily for me, my husband didn’t hesitate.  He accepted my infertility and the fact that adoption would one day be part of our life as a couple.  \n     As an elementary school teacher, I have always had a fondness for children.  I wouldn’t have chosen such a career path, if that were not the case.  While I will not carry a child in my body, I know that being a mother is what I am meant to be.  Not only have I prayed for the child that will change my life, I also have prayed for the courageous individual or couple that would make that possible.  I already respect the birthparent(s) of my child, and will always do right by them.  \n     I grew up in a small town in a home that was full of love and great memories.  My mother and father met in Jr. High School and have been together ever since.  They raised my sister and me in an environment that allowed us to succeed in school, be surrounded by a very large extended family and to enjoy as many extracurricular activities as we could handle.  Between dance classes, baton classes, music lessons, cheerleading practices, softball games, choir concerts, school musicals, track meets  and a number of other activities, I am amazed at the love, support and dedication my parents have shown. It has never wavered.  Today, my parents are not only my life mentors, they are my friends\n     Every Sunday, our family would attend church and often follow services with brunch.  My parents always felt that my sister and I needed to learn how to dine out and show manners outside the home.  For my sister and me, going to college was never a choice.  It was required by our parents.  And they made sure that we succeeded.  The drive and determination my parents had for me is what has allowed me to build a life of fulfillment and success.  I have completed college, obtained a Masters Degree and have a secure job.  I am married to the love of my life.  I am surrounded by countless friends and family members.  But…the one thing that is missing…that would make my life complete…is being a mother.  I want to give a child the same experiences my parents gave to me.  \n     I am a step-mother to an amazing and beautiful teenage girl.  When I married my husband, I felt as if she was a “bonus” to our relationship.  She and I share a special bond and I love her as if she were my own.  However, she did not come into my life until she was nearly a teenager.  I did not get to experience the things I want to experience with a child of my own.  First steps.  First words.  First haircut.  First day of school.  Classroom parties.  Birthday parties.  Learning to swim and ride a bike.  Nonetheless, she is an integral part of my life.\n     Today, my sister has 3 children that are eagerly awaiting a new cousin to play with and love.  My sister, who just completed her PhD program is happily married and is anxiously awaiting to be “the aunt I have been to her children.”  She is three years older than me and has always served as a role model to me.  We grew up extremely close, yet our interests were not very similar.  She enjoyed all things “academic.”  \n    I, on the other hand, always achieved good grades, but also enjoyed playing.  I was always using my imagination to create new games and crafts.  Nonetheless, we both grew up happy and can truly not think of a time in life where sadness set in.  \n     Our parents were, and still are, our biggest supporters.  My parents, who live less than 10 miles from us, think it’s their “duty” to give as much love to each of their grandchildren as possible.  My father, who is a man of great integrity and ethics, is newly retired from his job in “Corporate America.” My mother, who is witty and extremely generous, works as a secretary for a small, local business.  She hopes to retire soon, as well.  Their motivation?  “We want to spend as much time with our grandchildren as possible!”  I feel so lucky to have the relationship I have with them.  Christmases and other special holidays and events just seem more “magical’ because having my parents around just makes it that way.  I am lucky to be so close to my husband’s parents, as well.  They treat me as if I were born to them.   Any child that joins our family will have a heart that is filled with love. We are blessed with lots of family.\n      No words could ever express what I truly feel for the birthparent or parents of my possible child.  Because I have known for most of my life that adoption was my only means of having a child, I have always kept the parents of my possible child in my thoughts and prayers.  The respect and gratitude I have towards them will never be enough.  It may seem strange to pray for individuals that I do not know, but in a way, because I know the love I have to offer a child, I am able to know the respect and gratitude I have towards those that gave him/her life.  Life is precious, in all forms, and I will never take that for granted.  \n     Circumstances determine the life we all can have…including the child I am eagerly awaiting for.  The same goes for birthparents. I believe that circumstances will lead them to the choice of adoption.  And sometimes, circumstances are not to be questioned.  \n\nJust respected.  \n\nAppreciated.  \n\nHonored.  \n     \n     Our intentions are to always honor the birthparents of our child.  Our child will know of our deep desire to have him/her in our lives. \n      Our child will also know the deep desire his/her birthparents had, to make sure he/she would have the life full of love, support and family that only Michael and I can give.  For that, I will be eternally grateful. \n      I know that Michael and I will be attentive parents. \nI went to school in the same school system from Kindergarten through twelfth grade.  At 3 years old, I became friends with 3 girls, in my church Sunday school class.  To this day, those three girls are my best friends.  We have been there to support each other through the ups and downs in life.  The three of them have young children and I eagerly await introducing our child to them and their families.  \n     In high school, I was actively involved in activities and held a 3.8 GPA.  I was president of the student council and captain of the varsity cheerleading squad.  The experiences I had in high school were ones of great fun and memories.  I look back on those years with a smile.  \n     I went to a small, liberal arts college and obtained a degree in Elementary Education.  There, I made some significant friendships that sustain me through good and bad times to this day.  At least 4-5 times a year, my college friends and their families get together to play games, have cookouts and just laugh.  Our families have become close and we all enjoy these times together.  They, too, are excited about our adoption journey.  \n     Upon my college graduation, I obtained my teaching position.  I, first, taught English as a Second Language (ESL) in grades K-12.  Through the experience, I was able to appreciate various cultures, other than my own. It was an amazing experience.  I have worked in one of the state’s leading schools, and have established a wonderful career for myself.  Having taught Kindergarten, First, Second and Third grade, I am fully aware of the importance of laying a solid educational foundation for a child.  Michael and I intend to be actively involved in our child’s academic future and all that encompasses it.  \n     Soon after I began teaching, I obtained my Masters Degree in School Administration and went on to obtain a certification in School Principal.  My career has provided me with numerous moments of self-satisfaction and achievement…even being chosen as “Teacher of the Year,” in our regional area.  I have formed friendships and lifelong bonds with many coworkers, students and parents over the years.  In a tough economy, I feel lucky to have a job that I truly love, has a schedule that is flexible for a parent and is secure. \n     Aside from meeting my husband, marrying him and gaining a step-daughter, I have been blessed to have significant moments in my life that touch me each day.  At the age of 15, I was chosen to be the Godmother to my beautiful baby cousin.  At the time, my aunt and uncle saw, in me, the love I had for children and the longing I had always had…even at a young age…to be a mother.  Aware of my infertility, they chose me to baptize their daughter, my cousin.  That moment is one that I will never forget.  My godchild and I have a true closeness that has been built out of love and trust.   Now, a successful college graduate with her first "real" job, I have never missed a dance recital, school concert or formal dance that she took part in.  I was there to cheer her on…and shed some bittersweet tears…as she graduated from high school and college.  \n     As I get older, I have found that I am a person that genuinely appreciates tradition.  My godchild’s birthday is Christmas Eve…and every year, since she was one years old, she and I have gone out to lunch on her special day.  Each year, along with her birthday gifts, I present her with a new “Night Before Christmas” book.  This little tradition may seem insignificant, but it means a lot to both of us.  She has always told me that she can’t wait to read every one of those books to my child, someday.  Perhaps, a new tradition?  \n     Equally as significant was the birth of my first nephew.  Knowing the challenges my sister faced, due to her invitro procedure, the birth of my first nephew seemed as if it were a miracle, of sorts.  I will never forget that fall day.  Just weeks after September 11, 2001, I hopped on a plane and flew to be with my sister in another state, as she gave birth to my nephew.  The first night they spent in the hospital, I stayed, too!  I held him the entire night on the day of his birth.  I literally never went to sleep.  I took in every move he made.  Every sound he uttered.  I truly held a miracle that night.  I know that the feeling will be even more joyous the day I get to hold the child that I will get to raise.  I am known as the “favorite aunt” to my nephews and niece.  In fact, as I write this, I just got a phone call from my oldest nephew…he just got his first cell phone!  His first call…me!  I feel so grateful for moments like these.                                                                                   I have served as a bridesmaid in 21…yes, 21 weddings!  To be asked that many times is an honor.  Each of those times has been special to me and for different reasons.  When people get married, they want their day to be “perfect.”  To be asked by that many couples to have such a special role in their “perfect” day is humbling.  In turn, Michael and I had 32 attendants in our own wedding.  While our wedding day was filled with many people, from different stages of our lives, the most blessed part is the marriage we share today. I don’t take this for granted.  In fact, our “tradition” is making sure that we have a “date,” each month, on the date we were married.  We are anxious to involve a child in this special monthly tradition. \n     Before I was married, I bought my first home.  It was a learning process and one I took great pride in.  It was scary to sign so many papers and know that I was a homeowner, but it was equally as exciting.  Beyond the fun of decorating and having a place to call my own, I felt a sense of achievement for getting myself to such a place in life. To have worked hard in school, obtain a secure job and to commit to buying a home gave me a sense of pride.  Today, Michael and I share this same home.  Memories of our first days as a couple, family gatherings and fun times have been formed in this home.  We look forward to this home being the home we bring our child home to.  It truly is the memories that make a house a “home.” \n      Above all of these significant moments in life…the one I feel that is most significant is the moments we are living right now.  As a child, I played with baby dolls.  As a teenager, I was the babysitter of “choice” for many people in our community.  In college, I worked to help children in need by volunteering for the Children’s Miracle Network.  A few years into my teaching career, I became a teacher of “choice,” and each year my classroom is filled with children whose parents request me.  \n    Now…in this moment…my husband and I have taken the steps towards creating a family, through adoption.  With so much “GOOD” in my life, I know the “GREAT” will be the day we get to bring a child into our home.    That, in itself is significant beyond words.\n     Our dreams for our child are simple, yet complex.  With two parents, a step-sister, 4 grandparents, an aunt, uncle, 3 cousins, a large extended family and numerous friends…all waiting to welcome a child to our world, we know he/she will be loved and supported beyond belief.  We want our child to be healthy, happy and get a good education.  Even more, we wish for our child to grow up with a rich faith, a strong spirit and an understanding of how they came into this world.  Truth, honesty and good morals will sustain our child through life and guide him/her to learn from the mistakes he/she may make in life and also to soar to great heights from the successes he/she will achieve.  We want our child to grow to work hard and play hard.  To take pride in his/her work and all that encompasses it.   We want our child to appreciate the small and large things people do for him/her and just as important, appreciate the small/large things he/she does for others. We look forward to seeing life through the eyes of a child.  There is an innocence and a pure joy about viewing the world through a child’s simplicity.  It will surely be refreshing!  We are anxious to expand our family through the gift of adoption.\n     We will work hard to be the family we dream to be and be the family the birthparent or parents dream we will be.  We know we can make this happen and we are anxiously awaiting the day we can begin!\n', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'About Beth...A Mother&#039;s Hope...', 2395, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'html', 1349281797, 0),
(657, '     I''ve always known I wanted children.  I wanted to be the parent my parents were to me.  \n     During our courtship, my wife expressed to me her desire to have children and a family.  I, too, wanted the same thing.  She further told me that she was unable to have children, due to a past medical condition, that resulted in certain infertility. This was something I didn’t even need to think about.  Knowing that her sister had three children (two of which were adopted); I knew the love a family could have for children that were not biological.  As adoption being our only choice, I accepted that it would be the means to creating a family together, although a possibly difficult and lengthy process. We both agreed that an infant is what we would want to adopt.           \n     Being the “rock” in our marriage, when dealing with our infertility, makes me more certain than ever that adoption is the right choice for us. \n     Having grown up an only child, I sometimes wished I had siblings.  I grew up having cousins close in age, but never got to experience what it was like to have a sister and/or brother.  This is something I would like for my own child/children, if that is what is meant to be.  \n     I grew up in a happy home with my mother and father.  They had been married about three years before having me.  My parents have a strong marriage that has endured the “normal” ups and downs of life…losing parents, failed attempts at becoming pregnant, and the loss of jobs, due to the economy.  Today, my parents are still happily married, are healthy and are eagerly awaiting a new grandchild!  My mother is a homemaker.  She enjoys baking, music and crafting.  My father has a secure job with the state and also, is the owner of a small business.  He works hard and has always been the provider for our family. I have always admired his dedication to working and maintaining our home.  He is a man of great integrity and has been my most significant role model.   I work with him in our small, family business.   It provides us with a secure paycheck, as well as a somewhat flexible schedule.  In a few years, the plan is for me to take over the family business, with the possibility to expand. \n     Together, my parents have provided me with all of the necessities in life…food, shelter, clothing and an education.  Our family is Catholic and we attended church regularly, as I grew up.  I was extremely active in sports, as a child and teenager.  My parents were always there to support me, provide equipment and guidance and to cheer me on.  As a family, we enjoyed attending sporting events.   My parents were often the ones to transport many of my friends and even serve a “parents” and cheerleaders to those teammates that weren’t as lucky as me.  \n     As an only child, I saw my parents, in a way, be “parents” to so many.  Today, my parents are in good health and live less than 10 minutes from me.  I speak to them daily and we have a very strong and close relationship.  They have embraced my wife and consider her their other child.  They never miss a chance to tell us how much they love both of us. Luckily for me, in marriage, I gained two more loving and devoted parents with my in-laws. \n     I attended parochial school for the first 7 years of my education.  I received good grades and was considered a “well-behaved” student.  My mother was often seen at my school, helping out with the PTA.  Getting good grades and behaving were expectations my parents had for me.  In 8th grade, I transferred to the local public school, where I was equally successful.  I played basketball, football, track and baseball.  In my high school sports career, I lettered each year and to this day, still hold a few school records in track!  The friendships I formed in my early Jr. High years are still strong today.  Several of us still live locally and see each other on a regular basis.  We have served as groomsmen in each others’ weddings and have been there to support each other through life’s events…deaths of parents, births of children, succeses in our careers, etc.  \n     After high school, I began college and wanted to pursue a career in physical therapy.  With my grades, extracurricular activities and my SAT scores, I was accepted into the college of my choice.  However, my plans for my future changed, upon the birth of my daughter.  \n     My “high school sweetheart” and I were taken by surprise when we learned of our pregnancy as teenagers. While not planned, we accepted the situation and knew that having the baby was our only choice.   Upon the birth of our daughter, I transferred schools to be closer to my daughter and her mother.  I immediately took on a manual labor job at a local mill, in order to provide for our child.  For two years, I was able to work and go to school, but I then, found it too difficult to juggle.  I put my education on hold to work full time.  While the relationship with my daughter’s mother did not work out, I am proud of the relationship we still do have.  We have always parented together and put our daughter first.  I am fortunate in that we always got along for the sake of our daughter. This is not an easy thing to do when a child goes between two homes.   Both of our families embraced our daughter with open arms and have provided her with more love and support than one could imagine.  Today, my daughter is a teenager and is doing well.  She has grown into a beautiful young woman and is an important part of my life.  My wife treats her as if she was her own and vice versa.  The relationship the two of them have is one of closeness and love.  My daughter’s mother is, now married and has another child.  Due to our shared custody, we continue to get along and do what is best for our daughter.  We continue to communicate on a regular basis, for the good of our daughter.  While having a child, at such a young age was extremely difficult, I have been fortunate because of the love, support and sacrifices that have been given by our families.  My daughter often jokes that having 4 families (mine, my wife’s, her mother’s and her step-father’s) can be difficult to keep track of, but, come her birthday and Christmas, she is extremely spoiled and appreciative to have so many families! The situation couldn''t be better, and I consider myself very lucky that it worked out the way it did.\n     I have always been part of my daughter’s life.  I have seen her first steps, heard her first words and experienced her first days of school.  I provided her with her first pet. I have been there to lend support and offer praise, as she steers her way through her own life.  From Baptism, to First Holy Communion to Confirmation, I have been by her side in the church, as well.  I have been there to teach her how to ride a bike, to swim and to drive.  I have taken care of her when she was sick and pushed her to do better in school when I knew she could.  An avid horseback rider, my daughter is enrolled in a world class equine program, with aspirations of working with horses, in one capacity or another, as an adult.  I have supported her and helped to foster this talent, as she has grown.  An avid golfer, I have begun to teach my daughter the game.  I also enjoy cooking, and I enjoy the times she and I get to cook together.  These are experiences I have had with my daughter and I wish to share with another child, along with my life partner – my wife – by my side.  While I got to do these things, I was never able to do them as a family…a father, mother and child.  I look forward to the days ahead, as I get to experience fatherhood in a different way.  \n      With the apparent age difference between my daughter and a possible sibling, I do not foresee any difficulty in being the father to more than one child.  My daughter seems equally as excited to welcome a new sibling, or siblings, to our family.\n\n     As a person who became a teenage parent, I have full respect for any birthparent that makes the choice towards adoption.  I was lucky, in that I had A LOT of support (both financially and with family) to not have to make a difficult decision with my child.  As someone who wants a baby, with my wife, I also know the feeling of hope.  Adoption is a wonderful thing and I look forward to loving our adopted child with as much love as I have for my biological child.  \n      In addition, seeing how much my wife loves my biological child, I can see into our future with an adopted child. Having the same genetic line will make no difference to either of us.   We will both care for our child with endless love and support.  Because of the responsible and courageous decision of a birthparent, this will be possible for us.  I do not foresee any differences in parenting our adopted child versus my biological child.  I have enough love and support to give to both.  I am thankful for this.\n      In considering the important things that have happened in my life, my marriage and daughter, aside, I hope to use these things as a springboard for being a good parent to our baby.  My past achievements in sports have taught me lifelong lessons.  My hard work and success in sports serve as a metaphor to life.  If you work hard, you will find success.  Each sports achievement has been a significant part of my life.  More than the trophies, plaques and newspaper clippings that I have accumulated, I take with me the life lessons of hard work and perseverance.  The death of my fraternal grandfather was unexpected and weighed heavily on my heart.  Having been named after him…and my father…I always felt certain closeness to him…and obligation to make him proud.  As a teenager, I experienced his loss and I carry that with me today.  Because of it, I do not take advantage of family and having them around.  My family never wastes an opportunity to say...and show…our love for one another.       \n      Maintaining my childhood friendships into adulthood has been important to me.  Having no siblings, my friends feel like brothers to me.  While I have friendships from other stages of life, I can truly say that there is nothing like lifelong friends.  Those that knew me “when” and still stand with me today.  I am proud that we have maintained the close bond that we have.  To me, my friends are my extended family and I look forward to introducing our child to them.  \n      Beginning to work with my father in our family business has been significant to me on a few levels.  Not only have I learned a strong work ethic from my father, I have also learned to take pride in my work.  It is our family name on the business, and for that, I work even harder to do well.  My father has paved a small path for me, and I look forward to continuing down this road, as we transition from him, to me, in taking over the business.  Perhaps, I will one day, pass it along to my child.  \n      A significant event that did not happen was finishing my college degree.  While I am less than a year away from finishing, the daily demands of life got in the way of completing my education.  I sincerely regret not being able to finish, but the main reason behind not being able to finish has been worth it.  However, in being honest, it was not always “easy.”\n     These lessons from these significant life events in my life, are ones I want to carry on to my child.  Along with my wife, I want to teach my child the importance of hard work and perseverance, whether it be on or off a sports field.  I want to teach my child to value family and friendships. Often, the two can be intertwined.  I also want to teach the value of maintaining a pride in our family name.  It represents not just one, but all of us.  And finally, I want to teach my child the value of taking small opportunities to make bigger ones.  This includes attending and completing college.\n      Each of these things cannot happen alone.  They will be fostered and encouraged through the love, support and dedication that my wife and I, and our families will provide to our child.  We are excited to expand our family through adoption.  My heart, which has been filled throughout my life, is open and waiting to provide more love.\n', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'About Michael...A Father&#039;s Journey...', 2395, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'html', 1353469835, 0),
(658, 'We were ecstatic when we got the news that we were chosen to adopt our son Tommy through Adoptions Together in May 2010. We only had one week to get ready for his arrival and quickly put together a nursery. Our friends and family were thrilled about our good news and showered us with everything we needed. We were in the hospital when he was born and brought him home the next day.\n \nTommy has filled our lives with so much joy and we absolutely love being parents. His giggles, and hugs make us smile every day. He is a sweet little boy who enjoys playing with cars and trains, going on walks, and reading books. We still long for more children and know that Tommy will be a great big brother.\n', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Adopting Tommy', 2158, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'html', 1334073686, 0),
(659, '<b>From Julie:  Hi there!  I''m here to talk to you about Kirk.</b>  He is a very sweet and charming man who loves animals and children.  I knew when I met him that he was the one I would one day marry.  He has a very calm way about him and has an incredible sense of patience, too.   \n\nHe loves showing the kids how to work on cars or how to plow a field with one of his old tractors.  He is the type of dad who is up at night when the kids are sick....checking on them at 3am and making sure they are not too warm or too cold.   He''s also really good with homework and helps out while I am cooking dinner.  \n\nHe is an amazing teacher and I love hearing his stories about his students and the hilarious things they have to say.\n\n<a href="http://s1191.photobucket.com/albums/z475/juliea388/Facebook/Instagram%20Photos/?action=view&amp;current=539261_10150788928378343_632428342_11864849_2141359780_n.jpg" target="_blank"><img src="http://i1191.photobucket.com/albums/z475/juliea388/Facebook/Instagram%20Photos/539261_10150788928378343_632428342_11864849_2141359780_n.jpg" border="0" alt="http://instagr.am/p/JIh6gHkibw/"></a>', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'About Kirk', 2683, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'html', 1334090356, 0),
(660, '<p><span style="font-family:verdana, geneva;font-size:small;">We live in a neighborhood that consists of mostly families and retired couples and we are lucky to have a park just one street away. Our house has three bedrooms and a fenced in backyard. Our favorite room in the house is definitely the family room. We love to snuggle on the couch watching a movie and the floor is usually covered with Tommy’s toys.  We also enjoy having friends over and grilling in the backyard.</span></p>', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Our Home', 2158, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'text', 1342014231, 0),
