(841, 'Dear Birthparent,\n			\nAs I think about what I’d like to say to you, what I’d like for you to know about me, I first want to thank you for giving your child the ultimate gift of life, and for considering adoption. My husband and I previously adopted our son, Cormac, and because of that experience, my compassion and admiration for you could not be any stronger.  Through this letter and book, I hope you will gain an understanding of what kind of people Michael and I are, how our son would be as a big brother, and the kind of life that our children will lead.  Because we are parents already, we are in a unique position to show you our values as parents and as a family and what life would be like for your child.  It’s a tall order for just a small book, but I hope that it will be a good start so that you are informed and comfortable enough to seek more information about us if you choose to do so. With an open, honest dialogue between us, I know we could make your dreams for your baby come true.\n			\nI’ll start by telling you a little about me and my family.  I am 36 years old and used to work in the non-profit sector before deciding to become a stay at home mom.  I have a Bachelors of Science in sociology and women’s studies.  I grew up in a lower middle class family with an older brother and sister.  We didn’t have an excess of money, but enough to get by.  As a way of saving money, my dad grew a huge garden in our backyard.  My heart still melts thinking of being out in our garden, picking cucumbers and tomatoes, and eating as many green beans as I could right off the stalk.  We also had pear, fig, apple, and peach trees.  My dad would take a prideful picture of the prettiest apple to grow that season with us kids goofily smiling in the background. \n\nMy family is Catholic, and every Sunday we would go to church and then over to my grandparents for lunch.  My mom has 4 siblings and my dad has 5 siblings, and so with 29 cousins, you can imagine the ruckus we got into when we’d get together.  We made up so many games, some of which have been passed down to our children now.  I am incredibly close to my brother and sister.  We all live relatively close to each other and get together as frequently as possible.  Each of my siblings has 2 children, the oldest is 11 years old and the youngest is 6 years old.  They are young enough to want to play and be silly with my son, who is 2 years old, but old enough to treat him like a little brother and feel responsible for him.  It’s all very sweet to see.  For a long time, Michael and I were the only ones in both of our families without children; so we are known as the “fun” aunt and uncle. And now that we are parents, we’ve only become more playful with all the kids. If you have any concerns about how our families will treat an adopted child, let me put your fears to rest.  It absolutely does not matter to them how our children joined our family - only that they did.    Everyone is so happy for us, supportive, and pleased to see that we are on our way to completing our family by adopting our second, and last, child.\n			\nAs for me, I’d like to tell you a little about what my values are.  As a stay-at-home mom, I take my job very seriously in that I am building a family.  Every day, I think about what our values are, what kind of people we hope our children will be, what kind of parents we want to be, and then figure out ways to promote those values.  I want my children to always be learning - and I’m not necessarily referring to standardized schooling - but to always be studying things that they are interested in and that make them happy.  I will be honest and say that education is very important to me and I will raise my children to value a strong education; however, if that’s not in their cards, then I will support them to follow their desires.  I want my children to question everything and seek answers.  I want them to stand up for the underdog.  I want them to have the qualities of being able to put themselves in someone else’s shoes and to help others when needed.  I want them to be open and loving.  I want them to be polite.  I want them to have self-esteem and be proud of their endeavors, however small and trivial.  But, most of all... most of all... I am like every parent...  I am like you...  I want them to be happy.  \n\nI’d like to tell you a little bit about Michael and I and how we relate to each other, so you can know a little bit about how a child will see our relationship.  Michael, hands down, is the most supportive person I have ever met.  If I told him one day that I wanted to be a clown (don’t worry, I don’t), I have no doubt that he would reply by telling me that I should find a store that sells clown supplies and buy the big, round nose and silly clown shoes, and then that I should do an internet search for any clown schools in town, etc.  My point is that whenever I say I want to do something, he always puts a hand on my back to support me and push me towards that goal. I have known him since we were still in college and I have never known him to say something could not or should not be done.  And if he is like that with me and his friends, you can imagine what an amazing father he is!  When people ask me how I knew Michael was “The One,” I can tell them exactly.  I was walking home from class one day and I was thinking about him.  I was thinking about how since dating him, I had become interested in all these aspects of the world that I hadn’t learned about before.  And then I realized... He made me a better person.  He encouraged me to be the person I wanted to be.  I’m not saying that I wouldn’t have eventually done it on my own, but what I am saying is that I am so glad that I didn’t have to.  We have mutual respect for each other that I know everyone can see.  We do have disagreements, but we don’t “fight” and we never go to bed angry at one another.  We both understand that we have to work at our marriage every single day.  And I believe it shows.  Cormac sees us helping each other, working together, talking a lot, and hugging and giving kisses.  I hope, and expect, that our children will grow up to know what a healthy relationship looks like and will emulate it for themselves.  \n\nWe, also, value cultural opportunities and share a love of traveling.  For the past 6 years, we have gone on an international trip every year except this past year.  Our last trip, to Belgium and The Netherlands, was when Cormac was 9 months old.  We took a break this year as he was reaching his 2’s and we didn’t think that putting him through an 8-hour plane ride would be fair to him. When we become parents again, we will likely also take a break and in the meantime will enjoy traveling in the U.S.  We have traveled around England, Spain, Gibraltar, Estonia, Finland, Sweden, Mexico, Thailand, The Netherlands, and Belgium. Thailand was my personal favorite (it’s a beautiful country with the best food and the happiest people).  As a mom, I really enjoy traveling with children as there is heightened excitement experiencing it through their eyes. I look forward to sharing with my own children my life and the opportunities that were afforded to me; and to watch them find their own way of experiencing the world.\n			\nOur thoughts go out to you as you make this extremely difficult decision. We have the utmost respect for you. Whatever your circumstances may be, I commend you for considering adoption as I believe it is a reflection of the love you have for your baby. Should you choose us as the adoptive parents, we would love to have the opportunity to meet you and be as much a part of the pregnancy and birth as you feel comfortable with. We promise to raise your child with unconditional love in a safe and caring environment. Our dream is to become a complete family. Thank you for considering us.\n			\nThinking of you,\n\nKim', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Birthparent Letter from Kim', 3215, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'html', 1341607643, 0),
(842, '<p>Dear Birthparent,</p>\n<p>\nKim and I have been looking forward to completing our family many years and we''re so grateful that you are even considering us as adoptive parents. The decision to select adoptive parents has to be very difficult. Hopefully, we can help with this difficult decision by providing an excellent home, upbringing, and life for your child. We will always commit to taking care of our family beyond all other priorities. When we adopted our son Cormac just over two years ago, his happiness and health became our number one goal and the same would, of course, be true for your child!\n<p/>\nWe and our family have had a fantastic experience with our son and we’re ready to bring another child into our family’s life. Our families are as eager as we are to add new member. Kim''s family is large and filled with aunts, uncles, cousins, nieces, nephews, and grandparents - all of whom get along and play wonderfully with our son. That big family had become comforting and supportive of the three of us and are always so loving with our son. Most of Kim''s family family live nearby, making for fun holidays and visits throughout the year for. With all these people, there’s always a large gaggle of kids running around, laughing, and playing!\n<p/>\nMy family, though smaller than Kim''s, are equally warm and loving. My sisters each have children of their own who’re excellent playmates. My father and stepmother are extremely kind and doting with their grandchildren. My dad’s side of the family lives very near to us, so we can visit with them frequently.\n<p/>\nMy mother and stepfather are also looking forward to doting on a new grandchildren. My mother has been an elementary school teacher for over 20 years and she even won Teacher of the Year at her school recently for her gardening for kids programs. My mother and stepfather cherish the time they spend with our son and are excited to add another grandchild to their days of loving fun and play.\n<p/>\nKim and I have been together for 12 years. We''ve grown from being young adults, having just graduated from college, to the adults, to the parents we are today. We''ve been through many happy times and many challenging times, allowing us to get to know each other more than anyone else. Being a parent is a completely new, often difficult, but overall enriching and great experience to have with someone like Kim. Our son is a smart, cute, funny, and energetic little boy who always surprises us with what he comes up with and how he learns about the world. \n<p/>\nKim is a very caring and especially loving woman. She stays focused on the present and building out a pleasant life. At the same time, she manages to plan for an even better future family life. She''s compassionate, not to mention beautiful and loving. I''ve watched Kim evolve into an expert parent as we’ve raised our son: I can’t help but notice how our friends who have new children often ask her for advice. Kim puts so much care and thinking into every decision about our family and son.\n<p/>\nOur son, Cormac, has grown from a small baby to a bundle of fun that loves exploring the world or just playing a game of chase for hours on end. He makes fast friends with almost anyone, rarely hesitating to strike up a conversation with someone or ask them to play with him. Without a doubt, Cormac will befriend and cherish his new sibling - I can see them spending their days playing in the house, at the park, and in the backyard - the two of them always ready to go visit with more friends.\n<p/>\nBeing a father has been more rewarding and enjoyable than I’d imagined. I was looking forward to parenthood a great deal, but I couldn’t anticipate how wonderful it’s been. Raising a child is a daunting, all consuming task, but with Kim, my family, and the life we’ve created for ourselves we have an excellent foundation to see us through all the trials and thrills of raising a family. In addition to learning and becoming a better parent each day, my parents have given me a good example of how to raise children to discover their potentials and then pursue the goals and desires that will better and bring happiness to their lives.\n<p/>\nAs with both my mother''s and father''s family, our family enjoys frequently traveling to see the world, meeting people and experiencing many different cultures and climes. We benefit each time we meet someone new and discover a new part of the world and I''m eager to give my children this experience as well.\n<p/>\nSimilarly, the community that we live in is rich in possibilities for raising happy, smart children. My family encouraged and supported a good education from pre-school to college and beyond and I look forward to doing the same for my children. Our children will have the same opportunity to balance fun and work that my parents, family, friends, and Kim have helped instill in me.\n<p/>\nIn making this decision, I realize that you are placing a tremendous amount of trust in Kim, Cormac, and I. Hopefully this book, and our letters, will help you to get to know us better. As this is all such a big decision, we would be pleased to meet with you and would be happy to send updates and photographs to you ongoing. If you choose us, you can rest assure that we will raise your child in a loving and supportive family.\n<p/>\nUltimately, our hope is to raise a happy family, creating a fun, loving life for all of us. In helping to achieve that, we are forever thankful that you have considered helping us complete our family and thank you for thinking of us.\n<p/>\nWarm Regards,\n<p/>\nMichael', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Birthparent Letter from Michael', 3215, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'html', 1341608238, 0),
