(1010, '<p style="font-family:Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;color:#9900cc;font-size:14px;">My favorite thing to do is spend time with friends and family, whether that means to cuddle on the couch, go for a hike, go shopping, or share in prayer time. I like to do crafts, read, cook, and dabble in photography. I love hiking, swimming, going to the beach and spending time outdoors with my family. Most of my  free time is actually spent being mom and I wouldn''t change that for the world!</p>', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Hobbies of Crystal', 3117, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'text', 1347770126, 0),
(958, '<p><strong>Greetings: </strong></p>\n<p>It is seldom in life that we get to choose the road we travel down, but we almost always have the opportunity to choose our destination. Sometimes we may get sidetracked, but we must always have faith that we will make the right decisions.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Thank you for considering adoption and for considering us as your gift to your child. Looking at different profiles is an important step in this journey and we hope that they will help guide you to make a decision that will benefit both you and your child.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>Our Journey:</strong><br />We met during high school in 2001 and have been together as a couple ever since. Andrew popped the question during the summer of 2005 while we were visiting Duluth, our favorite place to visit in Minnesota. We tied the knot in June of 2007, settled into a two bedroom apartment, and enjoyed having a place to call our own. Soon after, Bridget was offered a full-time position and was nearing graduation; we started exploring different options for purchasing our first home. In the early spring of 2008, we purchased 3.5 acres of bare land from a family friend and custom designed a 1,900 square foot modular home with a full basement and two-stall garage. A few months later, family and friends helped us move from our tiny two bedroom apartment to our new home. Our home is located ¼ mile from Andrew’s parents’ farm and about 20 miles from Bridget’s parents.<br /><br />We have two dogs. Billy, an English Shepherd, joined our family in the spring of 2008 when he was a year and a half. We both felt that Billy needed a companion, so in the spring of 2009 we brought JJ home. JJ is a husky mix and was six months old when we picked him up. It is always a joy to see how excited they are to see us when we get home and they love watching their little sister (Halley) wave to them from the window. <br /><br />In the summer, we enjoy camping at state parks and spending weekends out at the lake. We both enjoy knee boarding, tubing, swimming, and playing at the park. We are excited to get active with local ECFE activities and other programs that community has to offer to families. <br /><br />We are members of a small Lutheran church located five miles from our home. Andrew is on the board of deacons and Bridget participates in the ladies’ aid group. Our values and beliefs will be passed on to our children through baptism, confirmation, and attending church on a regular basis. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>God’s Plan: </strong><br />Good health, family, friends, and a place to call home are just a few of the blessings that God has given us. We continue to put our trust in him and we know that in all things, God works for the good of those who love him.</p>\n<p><br />Family has always been an important aspect of our lives and starting a family of our own has always been one of our top priorities. Soon after we were married, we decided we wanted to start our family and after a year of actively trying, we started seeking infertility treatment. We sought treatment for two years and dealt with it by having trust in God and by accepting the fact that everything happens for a reason. Infertility has made us stronger, both individually and as a couple, and has brought us even closer together. We believe God has led us down this path and that He never gives us a situation we can’t handle. With His help and His guidance, along with support from family and friends, we knew we could make it through anything.</p>\n<p><br /><br /><strong>Our daughter’s story: </strong><br />On June 15, 2011, our life forever changed. Halley Isabelle was born. Words can’t begin to explain the joy we had in our hearts when we got to hold her for the very first time. She weighed 7 lbs. 11 oz., was 21 ¼ inches long and is absolutely beautiful. We were able to bring her home from the hospital the following day, which happened to be our wedding anniversary. We continue to keep in touch with Halley’s birthmother and immediate family through pictures and letters. There isn’t a day that goes by that we don’t think of them.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>We are amazed at how fast the last couple months have gone and can’t wait for her to have a sibling to grow up with. She loves playing and chasing her cousins around the house and learning new things from them. Grandma and grandpa enjoy spoiling her with new toys and clothes; our house has quickly filled up. Since the day she was born she has always been a strong little girl and continues to be in the top percentile for her height and weight. It amazes us how fast she can pick up on things and we love watching her grow into a unique individual. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>Us as parents:</strong><br />Through adoption, we were able to start our family and we are now looking to expand our family. We are hoping to adopt one or two more children and do not have a gender or nationality preference. No matter what the future holds, we will love our children with all our hearts and will fight to give them everything that they deserve. They will be our number one priority and we will do everything possible so that they can live a healthy and enjoyable life.</p>\n<p><br /><br />Bridget plans on taking eight weeks off again for maternity leave. Andrew will continue to work on the farm and be a stay-at-home dad. This allows us to give our children the attention they deserve and we have the peace of mind knowing they are always in good hands. Once a week, they will visit Bridget’s parents and spend the day at their house to give Andrew an opportunity to get a few extra things done outside and at the farm.<br /><br />As a family, we will continue to take vacations and camping trips. We look forward to showing them how to ride their first bike, how to catch a ball, and even drive their first car. We will be there for them through the good times and the bad and will help guide them down a path that is fitting for them as individuals. It will be important for us to teach our children right from wrong, from the beginning, and explain to them why we feel the way we do. It is also important for us to follow through on what we say and to practice what we preach. <br /><br />We both believe that we have had strong morals and values instilled in us by our parents and families, and we will pass those values on to our children. We want our children to have every opportunity to express themselves, and that includes being able to think for themselves and have their own ideas. Honesty, respect, trust, faith, and love are just a few of the values we will instill in our children.</p>\n<p><br />We believe that if our children are told early on that they are adopted, there will be plenty of opportunities to answer their questions. We plan on letting them know that they are adopted before they can ever understand what that means. There’s no reason to hide it. If questions arise before we’ve decided they are mature enough to understand, we will answer them at that point. If no questions are asked, we will still explain to them their life and their background and how they became a part of our family when we feel our children can comprehend, at least to a degree, what we are talking about. The fact that they are adopted is something that we will never hide from them. There is absolutely nothing wrong with being adopted, and we’ll be sure that our children know this.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>Thinking of you:</strong></p>\n<p>Although we are on different sides of the road, we are all traveling down the same road. If it is your wish, we are willing to meet with you before or after placement. This would give all of us the opportunity to get to know each other better; you could learn more about us as a couple and we could learn more about you so that we can one day share with our child. We can’t even begin to understand the emotions you are feeling and we recognize the magnitude of your decision. We admire you for considering adoption and will keep you in our thoughts and prayers and look forward to answering any questions you may have for us. Your child is a blessing from God and we know that you will make a decision that is best for your child.</p>\n<p><br /><strong>Andrew, Bridget &amp; Halley</strong></p>', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Birthparent Letter', 3546, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'text', 1345250377, 0),
