(1052, '<p>Stacie often says that John and Lydia are best friends and worst enemies. They make an awesome brother-sister pair. Last year when John went to Kindergarten Lydia found herself often longing for her playmate and friend. When it was time for Lydia to move into John’s Sunday school class the teacher told us that “No one could want a better big brother.” He protected Lydia and showed her the ropes, making sure she had a place at the table next to him. It’s not all roses, however, they can squabble and squeal with the best of them but Aaron and Stacie try to teach John and Lydia to be kind to each other. </p><br>\n\n\n<p>John started 1st grade this fall. He absolutely loves school. He is an excellent reader and works hard for \nhis teachers. He is a huge help to Stacie around the house as we’ve begun to introduce chores. He is a pro at riding his two-wheel bike, which has been the big deal of the summer.  He is a very cute little boy with lots to say and is in his prime for real-life heroes, i.e. policemen/fire fighters, as well as super heroes. </p><br>\n\n\n<p>John is a very tender-hearted little boy and has been praying every night that God will give us a baby. He’s not only a great big brother to Lydia, but as I watch him interact with babies and toddlers in our friends’ families I know that he would play a big role in being the proud, big, protective brother to an even younger sibling. </p><br>\n\n\n<p>John loves to read and I’m never surprised to find him on the couch with a book. He loves dinosaurs, Curious George, Veggie Tales, and Wild Kratts. We plan on putting him into basketball in December to see if that’s  something he will enjoy. We want to offer the kids opportunities so that they can then decide what they are passionate about. </p><br>\n\n\n<p>This is pretty typical Lydia. Hardly a day goes by without her coming up with some type of odd combination from her dress up clothes. She is a very silly, funny, energetic little girl. It’s hard to spend any time with Lydia without smiling or laughing. She is my little outgoing social bug, who loves being the center of attention, even if she does come across as shy in new situations.</p><br>\n\n\n<p>Lydia started 3-day preschool in September and she couldn’t be happier to be surrounded by friends for 1/2 the day. She loves the people, the art projects and the \nlearning. She is my little dancer and I hope to put her into ballet soon to see how she likes it.</p><br>\n\n\n<p>Where John is cautious, Lydia is adventurous. She usually doesn’t hesitate to try new things whether it’s putting her head under water or riding her scooter on the trampoline.  Lydia has a great imagination and most days she spends at least a small amount of time pretending she is a cat, dog, pony, or princess. In fact when she grows up she wants to be “a doggy, a mommy, and a princess.”</p><br>\n\n\n<p>Lydia still has such a sweet way of articulating words and is very emphatic when she speaks. I could listen to \nher talk for hours. She loves animals and will always ask to pet a dog if we see one when we’re out. I won’t be \nsurprised if she has a houseful of pets when she is grown up. She is a light in our life and everyday I’m thankful \nthat God placed her in our lives through the decision of her birth mom. </p><br>', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'About the Kids', 4645, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'html', 1351052039, 0),
(1053, '<p style="text-align:center;"><img style="vertical-align:middle;" title="John and Lydia" src="http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8335/8118126028_361cc8426d_n.jpg" alt="John and Lyddie" width="320" height="166" /></p>\n<p>Stacie often says that John and Lydia are best friends and worst enemies. They make an awesome brother-sister pair. Last year when John went to Kindergarten Lydia found herself often longing for her playmate and friend. When it was time for Lydia to move into John’s Sunday school class the teacher told us that “No one could want a better big brother.” He protected Lydia and showed her the ropes, making sure she had a place at the table next to him. It’s not all roses, however, they can squabble and squeal with the best of them but Aaron and Stacie try to teach John and Lydia to be kind to each other. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>John started 1st grade this fall. He absolutely loves school. He is an excellent reader and works hard for his teachers. He is a huge help to Stacie around the house as we’ve begun to introduce chores. He is a pro at riding his two-wheel bike, which has been the big deal of the summer.  He is a very cute little boy with lots to say and is in his prime for real-life heroes, i.e. policemen/fire fighters, as well as super heroes. </p>\n<p><img style="float:right;" title="Superhero John" src="http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8331/8118096624_5edd2cb256_q.jpg" alt="John" width="150" height="150" /><br /><br />John is a very tender-hearted little boy and has been praying every night that God will give us a baby. He’s not only a great big brother to Lydia, but as I watch him interact with babies and toddlers in our friends’ families I know that he would play a big role in being the proud, big, protective brother to an even younger sibling.</p>\n<p><br /><br />John loves to read and I’m never surprised to find him on the couch with a book. He loves dinosaurs, Curious George, Veggie Tales, and Wild Kratts. We plan on putting him into basketball in December to see if that’s  something he will enjoy. We want to offer the kids opportunities so that they can then decide what they are passionate about.</p>\n<p><br /><br />This is pretty typical Lydia. Hardly a day goes by without her coming up with some type of odd combination from her dress up clothes. She is a very silly, funny, energetic little girl. It’s hard to spend any time with Lydia without smiling or laughing. She is my little outgoing social bug, who loves being the center of attention, even if she does come across as shy in new situations.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><br />Lydia started 3-day preschool in September and she couldn’t be happier to be surrounded by friends for 1/2 the day. She loves the people, the art projects and the learning. She is my little dancer and I hope to put her into ballet soon to see how she likes it.</p>\n<p><br /><img style="float:left;" title="Lydia Fashionista" src="http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8467/8118110457_1b98598531_m.jpg" alt="Lydia" width="171" height="240" /><br />Where John is cautious, Lydia is adventurous. She usually doesn’t hesitate to try new things whether it’s putting her head under water or riding her scooter on the trampoline.  Lydia has a great imagination and most days she spends at least a small amount of time pretending she is a cat, dog, pony, or princess. In fact when she grows up she wants to be “a doggy, a mommy, and a princess.”</p>\n<p><br /><br />Lydia still has such a sweet way of articulating words and is very emphatic when she speaks. I could listen to her talk for hours. She loves animals and will always ask to pet a dog if we see one when we’re out. I won’t be surprised if she has a houseful of pets when she is grown up. She is a light in our life and everyday I’m thankful that God placed her in our lives through the decision of her birth mom. </p>', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'About the Kids', 4645, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'text', 1351052697, 0),
