(1055, 'We met in 1999 when we both attended the same poetry group in college. Although our poems were pretty dreadful, and our haircuts even worse, we saw something in each other from the very beginning. We became close friends as part of a larger group of friends and began dating in 2001. We were married in 2005.\n\nWe really are each other’s best friends. For us, that means that there’s no one we’d rather be with for the fun stuff (travel, hanging out with other friends, lazy summer mornings spent strolling around town) or the not-fun stuff (cleaning the kitchen, taking the car to the mechanic’s, going to the grocery store). On a typical night, you’ll find us sitting at a coffee shop. Mike will be slowly sipping his black coffee, playing on his laptop and making Char laugh. Char will be reading a novel- interrupting herself every few pages or so to update Mike on what the characters are doing  – or to share a story from her day.\n\nWe are a couple with 1,000 nicknames for each other and a million inside jokes. Mike makes an amazing cup of coffee (it’s quite a process) and takes beautiful photographs (many of which you can see on this site). Char loves to try new recipes, reads a ridiculous number of novels, and has mastered the art of baking the perfect chocolate chip cookie.\n\nWe know our life will change immeasurably when our baby comes and although we love our lives now we are so ready to become parents!\n\n      \n\nChar grew up in a large, loud family in Alabama. Her childhood is a blur of popsicles, family road trips and time spent playing with her three older sisters who were (and still are!) her closest friends. She cherishes the memories of exploring her hometown with her mom, putting on plays in her grandmother’s living room, and being dropped off at school every morning by her dad saying “I love you, mama will pick you up!” The sense of stability and joy was pervasive in her childhood, and she hopes to build that kind of home for her kids.\n\nMike grew up a half a world away in Poland, but actually our childhoods were very similar. Mike remembers long days playing with his sister, cousins and neighborhood friends. He was an active and adventurous kid…running through fields, playing lots of soccer, and dreaming up big adventures for himself and his friends. Mike’s greatest childhood adventure came when his family moved to the U.S. when he was 12. His parents decided to immigrate to Maryland to pursue more freedom and a better life. Mike quickly made Maryland his home – making new friends, learning English and eagerly exploring his new surroundings.\n\nFaith was an extremely important part of both of our lives as kids, and remains so today. Both of our families are Catholic and we learned a love of the faith from an early age through the example of our parents. We both feel that our faith is one of the greatest gifts our parents gave us and intend to pass that along to our kids.\n\nWe have always dreamed of becoming parents. Facing infertility together as a couple has made us stronger and more certain than ever that what we most want is to become parents. After months of prayer, thought, and conversation, we embraced adoption as our path to parenthood. We are so thrilled to be taking concrete steps down that path- come join us for the journey!', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Meet Us ', 4667, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'html', 1351471661, 0),
