(1137, 'Isaiah is seven. Bright, energetic, hilarious, and deeply loving, since babyhood he has known exactly who he was. He''s a busy kid, but he likes art best. We''re always amazed by the creations he makes from the big box of supplies we keep for him. (Nothing gets recycled or trashed in this house without first checking if it''s a good shape or material for art.) At his school where kids in different grades work together his teachers say he is a gentle teacher to the little ones, already showing signs of the loving, supportive big brother he will someday be.', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'About Our Son', 4774, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'html', 1353427266, 0),
(1139, 'When we were young we always said we''d have one baby and adopt another. We forgot for a while, trying to get pregnant again, but then we were reminded of the gift of having both the opportunity to experience the biological journey to a baby as well as the experience of opening our home to a baby looking for one. We also always said our child would be a child of color--partly our response to seeing the racial inequalities in the adoption system but mostly our wish to have the richness of a multiracial family. (One of the reasons we chose our town is that there are other families with adopted children, and most of those are children of color.) When it came time to fill out our adoption paperwork, our choice became clearer: with so many lifelong African-American and biracial friends, and with biracial cousins, we knew an African-American or biracial baby could find love, support, and see their own face reflected in a lot of loving aunties and uncles. Through our jobs we''ve had more education in cultural and racial ideas than most people, and we''re excited to continue to grow in that way.', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'About Race', 4774, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'html', 1353427311, 0),
