(1216, 'We have a four bedroom house that we can''t wait to fill with kids.  We live in a wonderful suburb in CT about 50 minutes from New York City.  There are lots of things to do nearby including parks, beaches and museums.  Our favorite is the Stepping Stones Museum which is perfect for kids ages 1-10.  The SONO Aquarium is also great for kids of all ages.  ', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Our House', 5093, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'html', 1362164111, 0),
(1217, '\n\nNoah was born on April 30, 2005. He is Whitney’s child from a previous marriage, but Matt has raised him since he was 3.  He is now 7 years old.  Noah loves anything that has to do with the army!!  Noah also collects turtles. Noah is a gentle and quiet spirit, much like his mother. He can be shy when you first meet him, but quickly warms up when you get to know him.  Noah is in the 2nd grade and his teacher says he is the best reader in his class!!! Noah is very close with his grandparents and his uncles.  We are so blessed to have such a wonderful son like Noah and can’t wait to watch him as a big brother! \n', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Our Child', 5151, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'html', 1359653342, 0),
(1423, '<p style="text-align:justify;">I’m a commercial interior designer and have owned my own business for nearly five years.  I work part time from our home.  We believe the early years of a child are very important, and decided to reduce my workload rather than rely on daycare.  I have a love of art and architecture.  I’ve designed my own Christmas cards since high school.  I also enjoy drawing abstract pictures and watercolor renderings and taking photographs.  I look forward to teaching our children how to draw and I hope they will enjoy being creative.  I enjoy being outside, taking walks, swimming and riding bikes.  I also enjoy yoga.  I love to travel and try out new places.  My favorite place to visit is the beach.  I would love to travel to Europe to see the amazing architecture.  I enjoy spending time with family – being a mom, watching movies, going to church, and visiting with relatives.  I have a large extended family and my cousin has triplets that we love to visit.  I''ve always dreamed of being a mom and I hope that we will be blessed with another child to join our family.  We have lots of love to share.</p>', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'About Anne', 2525, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'text', 1401848943, 0),
(1424, '<p style="text-align:justify;">Jacob isn’t our first adoption experience.  Anne’s brother, Joey, was adopted.  We believe that a child’s adoption should not be kept hidden from him or her.  Our approach is to make our children aware from the very beginning that they’re adopted, and we believe there’s value in having birthparent involvement provided the situation is not harmful to the child.  Jacob’s birthmother initially decided she didn’t want to meet us or receive updates; however, she changed her mind at the hospital.  It was an emotional experience but very satisfying, and we’re glad that we''re able to maintain regular contact. </p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"> </p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;">Since we''re pursuing a private adoption, there won''t be an agency between us to accommodate a closed or semi-open arrangement where contact information is not directly exchanged.  However, we recognize that we can’t understand how it feels to consider placing your child for adoption, and are willing to respect your decision regarding the level of openness you desire after placement.  While we prefer an open adoption, we would ultimately defer to YOU to determine what level of post-placement interaction, if any, is right for you and your family.  We’re willing to consider any arrangement including open grandparenting. We also recognize that your feelings regarding this may change over time.</p>', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Adoption Openness', 2525, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'text', 1381164041, 0),
(1221, 'January 2, 2013\n\nTo Whom It May Concern:\n\nI have known Whitney Burns for the last three years.  My special needs daughter, Ali, attends **** High School in Whitney’s Moderate and Severe Disabilities classroom.\n\nWhitney has been employed at ****** High School for four years as a certified MSD teacher.  For two of those years she worked one on one with a male student with severe autism.\n\nMy daughter has shown huge improvements since Ms. Burns has been her teacher and case manager.  Ali would shut down and not do her work at school.  Since Ms. Burns has been her teacher, she does her work and participates in her class.  Ali would argue a lot at school with adults and students.  At home, she would go into tantrums.  Ms. Burns helped our family with a behavior plan for home.  Whitney gave Ali permission to call her when Ali is angry and frustrated.  Ms. Burns always calms Ali down and Ali always apologizes to family members.\n\nWhitney has been a miracle worker for my daughter and family.  She has gone out of her way over and above any teacher I have ever known.  Whitney is a very special, caring, patient and loving person.  She started the Special Needs Talent Show at school that brought tears to my eyes.  Whitney’s students served a home cooked Thanksgiving lunch to staff members.  Each student had a job duty to perform under Whitney’s supervision.  Whitney has been doing community based instruction for seven years.  She started a special needs basketball team for her students.  Whitney, also, is on the principal advisory committee.  She received her second certification at Eastern Kentucky University on inter-disciplinary early childhood in Special Education.\n\nWhitney had a wonderful Christmas party for her students and family members at her home.  We all saw the love and care Ms. Burns had for her family and each and every student.  \n\n\n\nMatt is also a certified teacher at ******* Middle School.  He was head coach for the football and basketball team for fourteen years.  Matt has been a Science teacher for ten years.  \n\nMatt is very supportive of Whitney.  He came to her students` Talent Show and helped with her Christmas party.  I saw such love, care and great interaction between Whitney, Matt and Noah.  \n\nI am very fond of Whitney and her family.  I feel like I have known Whitney for a long time and feel a deep friendship with her.  I know Whitney and Matt would make wonderful parents for their adoptive child.\n\n.  \n\nSincerely,\n\n\n\nKaren L. Hoch', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Letter of Recommendation', 5151, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'html', 1359737589, 0),
