(1228, 'I have this image in my head. This image of a cupcake and a candle. I picture arriving with a two year old to a park with a playground. We walk out of the car and bring a picnic basket. We are joined by the birth family who get to laugh and play with the baby on the playground. We talk about how the baby is doing and I share pictures and stories. Maybe this will happen. . .maybe this is not something you would want or would make you happy – I don’t pretend to imagine what you might be thinking or feeling about contact with your baby after the adoption. However, I thought we should clarify what we are thinking. . . so you can make a decision with more information then “semi-open.”\n\n             We would love to have an annual celebration with the birth parents of our adopted child. We have been told over and over again that some birth parents don’t want that and we need to be understanding. . . but maybe you do. So, we are going to propose it. Maybe once a year you would be interested in having a “Family Party” where we could light a candle and celebrate that you made the choice to place your beautiful child up for adoption. . .and that because of that, we are a family. There is no pressure. We are clear about what we would love to have, willing to have, and what we are hoping for. . . .But we would never consider denying the critical role that you play as the birthparent in the life of the baby.\n\n             So, we wanted to clarify . . . since “semi-open” seems so vague. We are open to sending photos and letters through our agency every year. We are open to an annual visit and celebration in a neutral location where we could light a candle. . .play. . .eat a cupcake. . .and celebrate and remember the gift that God gave you. . .and the miracle that you chose us to be the baby’s adopted family. What do you think about my image of an annual cupcake and candle? ', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Candle and a Cupcake: What we mean by &quot;Semi-Open&quot;', 