(1333, '<p> </p>\n<p style="text-align:left;"><span style="font-size:small;font-family:''arial black'', ''avant garde'';">         Sam''s                                                                                                         Lori''s</span></p>\n<p style="text-align:center;"><span style="text-decoration:underline;font-size:medium;font-family:verdana, geneva;">Favorites</span></p>\n<p style="text-align:center;"><span style="font-size:small;"><em>Travel Destinations</em></span></p>\n<p>         England                                                                                                       Disney World</p>\n<p><em><span style="font-size:small;">                                                       Sports</span></em></p>\n<p>          Soccer                                                                                                           Soccer</p>\n<p><em><span style="font-size:small;">                                                  Children’s Books</span></em></p>\n<p>       The Gruffalo                                                                                                    Monkey Puzzle      </p>\n<p><em><span style="font-size:small;">                                                       Cuisine</span></em></p>\n<p>        Chinese                                                                                                               Italian</p>\n<p>                                                                     <a href="http://www.parentfinder.com/media/users/LoriandSam/honey_moon.jpg">honey_moon.jpg</a></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Our Likes', 5699, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'text', 1368670007, 0),
(1334, '<p><img src="http://www.parentfinder.com/media/users/LoriandSam/honey_moon.jpg" alt="" width="1193" height="795" />In 2002, against both of our better judgment, we agreed to meet on a blind date, encouraged by the middle school students and their parents who Lori was teaching at the time and Sam was coaching.  By the next day we were in a serious relationship and within two weeks we were planning a trip back to England for Christmas to meet Sam''s family.  Sam had forewarned them he was bringing home the girl he was going to marry.  Although Lori agreed within a few short months that an engagement was imminent, she made Sam swear he would not ask her until at least a year of dating. After nine or ten months, Lori started to complain about a lack of a ring!  Sam ( a British Citizen) had to renew his work visa, given his plan to return back to the UK had changed so dramatically!  After a Jewish based ceremony at the Philadelphia Cricket Club in August of 2004 we enjoyed a honeymoon in Jamaica, followed by a trip to England to repeat our vows at a Christian based service in front of our UK family and friends, plus a few travelers from the USA.While the instant attraction from that first date has not dwindled in the slightest, it has given way to a deeper understanding that without each other, neither of us are complete.<br />Having spent a large part of our professional lives working with children, we were both ready to start growing our family shortly after we were married and presumed the process would be straight forward and immediate.  However, after several months of trying to conceive without success, we sought fertility treatment.  After a great deal of expense physically, financially and most noticeably of all, emotionally, we took a break from treatment having been told we were in the 1% of infertile couples that are classified as "unexplained."  During that break from treatment we conceived naturally and have since devoted our lives to the miracle that is now our four-year-old daughter.  A few years ago we started to try to conceive a sibling for Ellarose but ran into the same issues we faced the first time around.  This time we only endured about 9 months of treatment, assessments and surgeries in an attempt to have another child.  Although we do not feel quite the same grief and devastation we felt the first time, the three of us still feel our family is not yet complete.  After many discussions as to the appropriateness of adoption for our family, aided by Lori''s unique understanding of the subject, having been adopted herself and having a special, unique relationship with her birthmother, we are in complete agreement that not only is it something we feel is right for us, we feel it is the very reason why we have the "unexplained infertility" issue in the first place.   We truly believe we are well prepared and destined to become adoptive parents to a child and we are able to offer them a comfortable and loving home and more importantly, a close and loving family.  That "unexplained" part of our diagnosis is no longer a mystery to us; it is easily explained, as it has led us down this path.<br />We love to take family trips as often as possible, visiting friends and family in Toronto and of course England, where Ellarose gets excited to see her cousins and Grandparents and the rest of the very tight extended family.In the fall and winter we take trips to the mountains to snow tube and ski and we love to take trips to Disney World. In the spring and summer we like to go to the beach with our friends and family, although most of the time is spent doing anything but lying in the sun! For all those days we can’t spend on vacation, we are fortunate enough to live in a beautiful home that has a huge yard, surrounded by trees, which becomes the perfect setting to play, have cookouts, explore and relax. During the winter, we have plenty of space indoors to play or to unwind watching a movie together.Our whole family is very active. Lori and Sam still play soccer regularly and Sam does a lot of coaching.Ellarose loves to play outside or go to her swim, dance or soccer lessons. However, her Grandma was thrilled last year when she to appeared on stage next to her in a musical!Thank you for your the time you have taken to read this brief account of how we have started to become a family. We have so much love to give another child and the three of us can''t wait for our family to grow again.</p>\n<p><img src="http://www.parentfinder.com/media/users/LoriandSam/honey_moon.jpg" alt="" width="1193" height="795" /></p>', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'A Little More About Us', 5699, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'text', 1368670549, 0),
(1335, '<p><img src="http://www.parentfinder.com/media/users/LoriandSam/honey_moon.jpg" alt="" width="450" height="300" /></p>\n<p><img src="http://www.parentfinder.com/media/users/LoriandSam/honey_moon.jpg" alt="" width="750" height="500" /></p>\n<p>In 2002, against both of our better judgment, we agreed to meet on a blind date, encouraged by the middle school students and their parents who Lori was teaching at the time and Sam was coaching. By the next day we were in a serious relationship and within two weeks we were planning a trip back to England for Christmas to meet Sam''s family. Sam had forewarned them he was bringing home the girl he was going to marry. Although Lori agreed within a few short months that an engagement was imminent, she made Sam swear he would not ask her until at least a year of dating. After nine or ten months, Lori started to complain about a lack of a ring! Sam ( a British Citizen) had to renew his work visa, given his plan to return back to the UK had changed so dramatically! After a Jewish based ceremony at the Philadelphia Cricket Club in August of 2004 we enjoyed a honeymoon in Jamaica, followed by a trip to England to repeat our vows at a Christian based service in front of our UK family and friends, plus a few travelers from the USA. While the instant attraction from that first date has not dwindled in the slightest, it has given way to a deeper understanding that without each other, neither of us are complete. Having spent a large part of our professional lives working with children, we were both ready to start growing our family shortly after we were married and presumed the process would be straight forward and immediate. However, after several months of trying to conceive without success, we sought fertility treatment. After a great deal of expense physically, financially and most noticeably of all, emotionally, we took a break from treatment having been told we were in the 1% of infertile couples that are classified as "unexplained." During that break from treatment we conceived naturally and have since devoted our lives to the miracle that is now our four-year-old daughter. A few years ago we started to try to conceive a sibling for Ellarose but ran into the same issues we faced the first time around. This time we only endured about 9 months of treatment, assessments and surgeries in an attempt to have another child. Although we do not feel quite the same grief and devastation we felt the first time, the three of us still feel our family is not yet complete. After many discussions as to the appropriateness of adoption for our family, aided by Lori''s unique understanding of the subject, having been adopted herself and having a special, unique relationship with her birthmother, we are in complete agreement that not only is it something we feel is right for us, we feel it is the very reason why we have the "unexplained infertility" issue in the first place. We truly believe we are well prepared and destined to become adoptive parents to a child and we are able to offer them a comfortable and loving home and more importantly, a close and loving family. That "unexplained" part of our diagnosis is no longer a mystery to us; it is easily explained, as it has led us down this path. We love to take family trips as often as possible, visiting friends and family in Toronto and of course England, where Ellarose gets excited to see her cousins and Grandparents and the rest of the very tight extended family. In the fall and winter we take trips to the mountains to snow tube and ski and we love to take trips to Disney World. In the spring and summer we like to go to the beach with our friends and family, although most of the time is spent doing anything but lying in the sun! For all those days we can’t spend on vacation, we are fortunate enough to live in a beautiful home that has a huge yard, surrounded by trees, which becomes the perfect setting to play, have cookouts, explore and relax. During the winter, we have plenty of space indoors to play or to unwind watching a movie together. Our whole family is very active. Lori and Sam still play soccer regularly and Sam does a lot of coaching. Ellarose loves to play outside or go to her swim, dance or soccer lessons. However, her Grandma was thrilled last year when she to appeared on stage next to her in a musical! Thank you for your the time you have taken to read this brief account of how we have started to become a family. We have so much love to give another child and the three of us can''t wait for our family to grow again.</p>', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'A little more about us', 5699, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'text', 1368703801, 0),
(1336, '<p> </p>\n<p><img style="margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;" src="http://www.parentfinder.com/media/users/LoriandSam/loriandsam_becs_wedding.jpg" alt="" width="279" height="300" /></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><span style="font-family:''arial black'', ''avant garde'';font-size:small;">OUR STORY</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family:''comic sans ms'', sans-serif;font-size:small;">In 2002, we agreed to meet on a blind date.  By the next day we were in a serious relationship and within two weeks we were planning a trip back to England for Christmas to meet Sam''s family. Sam had forewarned them he was bringing home the girl he was going to marry. Although Lori agreed within a few short months that an engagement was imminent, she made Sam swear he would not ask her until at least a year of dating. After nine or ten months, Lori started to complain about a lack of a ring! Sam ( a British Citizen) had to renew his work visa, given his plan to return back to the UK had changed so dramatically!  In 2004, we got marrid in the United States and had a quick honeymoon in Jamaica.  Then we returned back to the UK to celebrate our vows and celebrate our new lives together.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family:''comic sans ms'', sans-serif;font-size:small;">While the instant attraction from that first date has not dwindled in the slightest, it has given way to a deeper understanding that without each other, neither of us are complete. </span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family:''arial black'', ''avant garde'';font-size:small;">WHAT WE ENJOY</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family:''comic sans ms'', sans-serif;font-size:small;">We love to take family trips as often as possible, visiting friends and family in Toronto and of course England, where Ellarose gets excited to see her cousins and Grandparents and the rest of the very tight extended family. In the fall and winter we take trips to the mountains to snow tube and ski and we love to take trips to Disney World. In the spring and summer we like to go to the beach with our friends and family, although most of the time is spent doing anything but lying in the sun! For all those days we can’t spend on vacation, we are fortunate enough to live in a beautiful home that has a huge yard, surrounded by trees, which becomes the perfect setting to play, have cookouts, explore and relax. During the winter, we have plenty of space indoors to play or to unwind watching a movie together. Our whole family is very active. Lori and Sam still play soccer regularly and Sam does a lot of coaching. Ellarose loves to play outside or go to her swim, dance or soccer lessons. </span><span style="font-family:''comic sans ms'', sans-serif;font-size:small;">However, her Grandma was thrilled last year when she to appeared on stage next to her in a musical! </span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family:''arial black'', ''avant garde'';font-size:x-small;"><br /></span></p>', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'A Little More About Us', 5699, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'text', 1381666903, 0),
