(1387, '<p>Please click <a href="http://www.parentfinder.com/profileflipbook/1457-BruceandHeather/1457-BruceandHeather.html" target="_blank">here</a> to view our (Bruce and Heather''s) profile flip book. The way the file is formatted makes it flip sideways. Our apologies ~ this is not an accurate representation of our parental skills. <img title="Tongue out" src="http://www.parentfinder.com/plugins/tiny_mce/plugins/emotions/img/smiley-tongue-out.gif" border="0" alt="Tongue out" /></p>', '1', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Our E-book Profile', 1457, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'text', 1371599168, 1),
(1402, '<p><strong>MY ADOPTION STORY</strong></p>\n<p>  Ever since I can remember I knew I was adopted.  My parents read me stories about being adopted and tried to explain that I was not "created" by them.  I knew I did not look like any of my family members and also had an athletic talent, not a theatrical side like my Mother or a drive for reading the newspaper like my father.  I never minded the fact that I did not look like anyone else or that I had different interests, but there were times when I did have questions about myself, such as, "Where does the dry skin come from?" or "Why am I the only one that likes Italian food?"  Little did I know my questions were soon going to be answered.  </p>\n<p>Just before my 18th birthday my father sat me down at the table after school and said, "Lori I have something to tell you."  I said, " I know, my birth mother wants to meet me." He had a puzzled look on his face, paused for a moment and then answered with a simple "yes."  </p>\n<p>I did end up meeting my birthmother shortly after and yes, my questions were answered.  We do have a relationship now that consists of phone conversations and visits every few months.  </p>\n<p>My main reason for writing this is that I feel I can provide personal experiences and may be able to answer any questions your precious child may have while they are growing up.</p>\n<p><strong><br /></strong></p>', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Lori&#039;s Adoption Story', 5699, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'text', 1373300937, 0),
(1388, 'Thank you for taking the time to look at my profile and learn more about my life and story. I am overjoyed and hopeful to be approaching a possible adoption.  My husband and I tried for years to have a child and went through many rounds of fertility treatments, which led to two miscarriages and much heartache.  When my husband died a few years ago, I feared my chance to have a family had died with him. Adoption offers me a possibility to realize my dreams and to give a child a wonderful life and a bright future. I long to be a mommy:  the one who kisses scraped knees, serves tomato soup to cure sniffles, and checks beneath beds for monsters.  I pray one day I will have the opportunity to help with math homework, read bedtime stories, and catch fireflies.  Thank you for taking the time to consider me.\n\n \n\nI honor you for the courageous decision you have made: in looking at all the options for securing your baby''s future. I want you to know that I am prepared to give this child a life filled with love, protection, and opportunity. I have been blessed with many wonderful things in my life: a supportive and nurturing network of friends and family, a fulfilling and exciting career as a professor, the resources to pursue my dreams, and a beautiful home in a university town. \n\n \n\nI have also had to endure some unbelievable hardships: most notably, my husband''s tragic death. My life experiences have shaped the person I have become. Despite the loss and pain I''ve experienced, I hope to continue to live each day to the fullest -- to appreciate the small things and to make a positive contribution to life.  The opportunity to share my life with a child would be a miraculous blessing and I thank you for considering me.\n\n \n\nI am a professor of engineering and feel I have the best career in the world!  I very much enjoy teaching and mentoring students and my research is exciting and has the potential to make a positive impact on the world.  This career also affords me an amazing degree of flexibility.  I have three months off in the summer, six weeks in the winter, and control over my time during the rest of the year.  This will be very helpful, should I be fortunate to have a child in my life.  Also, living in this academic community, I would be able to provide a child with excellent educational opportunities and would encourage and nurture his/her strengths and talents.\n\n \n\nI live in a beautiful small town with excellent schools, a diverse population, and many family-oriented community activities, such as: weekly events at the local farmer''s market, outdoor children''s movies, a children''s museum, weekly family-friendly outdoor concerts, several major street festivals, holiday parades, and many sporting events and activities. A real estate site, www.homes.com, ranked this town #1 on its "Top 10 Cities to Raise a Family" listing.  Bloomberg''s Businessweek ranked it as the "Best Place in the U.S. to Raise Kids." Educational and economic information, crime rates, amenities, air quality, and diversity were factors considered in the nationwide ranking.\n\n \n\nMy home is a lovingly restored, 4-bedroom, 1888 farmhouse on a picturesque small horse farm, just three miles from the university campus. \n\n\n \n\n \n\nI live here with my two fluffy cats, Squishy and CiCi, and my Bichon Frise, Buffy.  They are all very friendly and enjoy the company of children.  \n\n \n\n \n\nPeople describe me as a light-hearted, curious, playful, extroverted, high-energy person.  In graduate school, I was voted “Most Likely to be Smiling” by my peers for three years in a row.  I love to be physically active and to play:  traits that seem to draw small children to me. \n\n \n\n \n\nI have a very close, loving, and supportive extended family of cousins, aunts, and uncles.  We are diverse: among us are Caucasian, Hispanic, Asian, and African American, and multi-racial ethnic heritages.\n\nI am truly blessed to have an extensive network of friends in this college town and beyond.  Since I have lived here all of my adult life, I have dozens of friends whom I have met through various hobbies, the church, my work, and volunteer groups.  Because I grew up in a major city in the Northeast, where there was considerable ethnic and racial diversity, my friends in childhood were primarily African American and Latina.  Today, although I live in a small town in the South, I''m thrilled that the large university attracts a diverse population of people.   Therefore, I continue to enjoy a diverse social circle.\n\nI am very actively engaged in my church community:  The Unitarian Universalist Congregation.  I am currently an advisor of the middle school youth group and was previously advisor to the high school youth.  We have a vibrant and thriving church community, with over 200 members and many families with small children. The Sunday School program is very popular and the kids love it!  UUC Sunday School teaches children about all major world religions and instills in them progressive values, such as:  respect for the inherent worth and dignity of all people, good stewardship of the earth, and the importance of active citizenship in community.\n\n \n\nThank you for taking the time to read my letter.  I wish you strength, courage, and serenity, as you move through this challenge that life has presented you!\n', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Letter', 5836, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'html', 1371140364, 0),
