(1400, 'Growing up in Goodland, KS was a wonderful experience as a child.  Goodland is a small town in western Kansas with a population of about four thousand people.   I was the youngest child in my family, and I had an older sister and brother.  My father, Dale, worked as an appliance repair technician, and later he owned his own repair business.  My mother, Linda, worked several jobs as an administrative assistant for the schools, and later she became and still works as the Sherman County Clerk.  I have one sister, Shawna, who is six years older, and one brother, Jeremy, who is two years older.  As a child, living in a small town provided a safe environment to grow and learn.  I had great teachers who fostered my interests in science and math.  I have many friendships that started in grade school and continue to this day.  In high school I was active in many academic groups, and I also was a long distance runner in cross country and track.  \nMy family, growing up, was loving, supportive, and had a strong sense of togetherness.  My dad exemplified what it means to work hard every day.  He instilled in us kids a strong work ethic and a commitment to family.  My mother instilled a great many qualities, one of these being to never give up and never stop trying.  She was always very supportive of my activities, whether it was academic, sports, or choir.  I also grew up close to both of my grandmothers, and enjoyed spending time with both of them. \nOur family is still very close, and even though we are spread out over Kansas and Colorado, and don’t get together as often as I would like, we have a great time when we do.  My family plans a vacation every year, and in the past few years we’ve been to Mexico, the Rockies, Branson, and several lakes in Kansas.  We always have a lot of laughs when we get together.  \nOn my side of the family, my sister and her husband, Tony, have three wonderful girls, Mackenzie, Emily, and Addison.  My brother and his wife, Katie, have two boys, Reid and Nate, and one girl, Bree.  They are all very sweet, caring, and fun kids. \nMichelle and I were introduced by a mutual friend in 2003, and we right away hit it off.  We shared common interests growing up, in music, and in humor. I found her to be very pretty with beautiful blue eyes and a great laugh. I was also drawn to her intelligence and her fun personality.  We continued to date several years before being engaged in September, 2005, and being married on April 29th, 2006.  I value Michelle as a caregiver, and her unconditional love and support.  She is thoughtful and considerate of others. It’s these qualities that will make her a great mother.  We share a love of camping, boating, and I’ve even gotten her to enjoy fishing, even when she has to bait her own hook!\nAlthough we do not have children, we do love our dog as if she was one.  Our dog Mia has been a part of our family for almost 10 years, and she is a very kind and loveable golden retriever.  She loves more than anything to spend time outside with us, and can seemingly play fetch for hours.\nI would describe my personality as a reserved, rational, independent, and adventurous spirit.  I easily make friends and am very loyal, trusting, and generous to those close to me.  I am somewhat of an introvert, and enjoy time alone to think and make decisions.  I believe this helps me be a good listener and a patient teacher.  I have always had a drive to figure out how things work, and I enjoy working on projects that require logical analysis.  I believe people should be treated with fairness and equity.  I am an action oriented person. I like to be up doing things.  I also enjoy adventurous activities like boating and wakeboarding.  I like the opportunity to work in my garage, where I have developed a hobby of woodworking and carpentry.  Over the years, I have accumulated enough tools to complete a variety of different projects.  Overall, I am an optimistic, cheerful, trusting individual.  I believe that I possess good qualities to teach and instill strong values as a parent.\nSpiritually, I am of a Catholic Christian background.  However, I was taught to be accepting and sympathetic to those of other faiths and spiritual backgrounds.  My faith has given me a strong commitment to helping others, and treating others as I would like to be treated.\nUpon graduating pharmacy school in 2002, I have worked as a pharmacist in Manhattan, KS.  I have worked as a hospital pharmacist the last 9 years.  I find my work very fulfilling.  Every day I make an impact by helping patients, nurses, and physicians.  In my job, I review medication orders from physicians, and ensure the safe and effective delivery of these medications to our patients.  I also answer drug related questions from patients and other health care professionals. The part of my job that I enjoy the most is programming our pharmacy system software to prevent drug related errors from reaching our patients.  Another satisfying aspect of my job is the camaraderie that exists in the pharmacy.  We are a tight knitted crew that work really well together, and also have fun outside of work.\nInfertility, unfortunately, has been a dark cloud over our marriage the last 5 years.  Our doctors have told us that we have what is called unexplained infertility, although there could be some issues with the quality of Michelle’s eggs.  Regardless, it has been a challenge, and a process of grieving the fact we cannot conceive our own child.  We still yearn to be parents, because we feel that there is lot of love for us to give a child, even if it is not our own biological child.\nIf we are blessed to become adoptive parents, I feel that I could provide a loving and safe environment for the child.  I will be a good listener, and be a patient father.  Michelle and I also have decided that in order for the child to grow up healthy, that we would maintain any level of openness necessary for that to happen.  \nThanks for reading and God Bless!\n', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'About Wes', 5705, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'html', 1372202306, 0);
