(1404, 'Dear Birth Parent(s)\nWe are Whitney and Tyler and we are honored that you have considered us to be adoptive parents! After two years of the pain and heartbreak of infertility, we have turned to adoption, and this seems to be the path we should have take all along. Adoption has been and exciting and very positive situation for us so far. We hope to find a birthmom or family that we can remain close friends with over the years and watch their child grow together. \n\nWe''ve had a hard time writing birth parent letters because we hate the thought of "selling ourselves" to you. We want you to choose us because you feel we are the right match for you and your baby, not by something we''ve said! So we will simply tell you the highlights of our life and we''ve included some FAQ''s that we''ve answered on agency applications. We hope to hear from you soon! \n\nDescribe yourselves: Tyler and I are high school sweethearts. We''ve been together for over 8 years, and married for 3. We finished high school and college before getting married. Whitney is a first grade teacher, and Tyler is a sales representative for chain stores such as rite aid, walgreens, etc. We both have excellent family hours, weekends off, and Whitney has summers off. \n\nWhat is your marriage like?  We have been best friends for years. We spend the majority of our time laughing, wrestling and being silly. We talk and text frequently throughout the day and are basically inseparable.  Two years of infertility has really brought us closer as we have persevered through so much stuff! \n\nDescribe your home: We have  lived in our home for 4 years, but have lived in this city since we children. Our house is small but cozy. 3 bedrooms, 2 bathrooms, fenced backyard, neighbors with small children, excellent school district, very safe neighborhood. We are close to parks and public pools.  \n\nWhat do you do together: We love to travel and try to take a vacation every year. We love to watch movies and curl up on the couch together. A typical evening includes grilling out on the back patio and playing with our dogs or taking a walk. \n\nHow do you handle your disagreements?  \nThese are usually rare and quick. We say what needs to be said and move on. We learned very early on in our relationship that cold shoulders and hinting around problems just drove both of us nuts. If we''re mad we say it and why, and we move on. We are usually laughing again after ten minutes. \n\nHow do you manage your money?  \nWe have done a good job with our money after seeing many others our age jump into a lot of debt. We have no credit cards whatsoever. If we want to do something expensive, we save. We have our own version of "Dave Ramsey cash flow" system that seems to work for us. We have no student loans or debt besides our mortgage. We do not have car payments, and we are paying for my grad school one semester at a time with cash.  We do plan to take a loan to pay for adoption. Seeing as we are in good shape otherwise, we know we can afford one payment. \n\nWhat do other members of your family think about your decision to adopt? \nOur families are 100% supportive. They have watched us struggle to add a child to our family and they have been so wonderful throughout every step. We have already had one baby shower, and the entire family helped us with an adoption yard sale in the spring. I can''t wait to introduce a little one to them! It will be quite the amazing homecoming when the time comes. We have  a large family with many brothers, sisters, aunts, uncles and cousins who will be spoiling this little one rotten! \n\nWhat are your attitudes and values on child rearing? \nWe are both very fun loving and want to raise happy and healthy children.  We also tend to be strict and we want to raise very respectful children who are disciplined. We agree that we want our family to be active and spend more time outdoors than in. We want our child to attend church and have the support system of the church. We want our family to be a priority and we plan to build in time just for us and protect it. \n\nHow would you discipline a child?  \nSeeing as we are a teacher/ coach, we are very good at discipline. We plan to use time-out/ redirection with young children until they are able to reason. After that point, discipline needs to be an opportunity to teach appropriate behaviors. We believe you need to discuss with the child what they did, why it was wrong, and how to act in the future. We do not believe in physical punishments, but we will remove privileges as necessary.  It is important to us to also model Godly behavior and good values to our children so they may learn by example. \n \nDo you plan to raise your child with religious training and values?  \nYes, we want our child to have a good moral compass and as sense of right and wrong. We don''t plan to force religion on any child, but we want to expose them to our faith and make sure they are familiar with the Bible so they may make informed decisions about their faith when the time comes. Being raised in the church helped us so much as far as being on the right path and making smart decisions, so we want this for our child as much as possible.  \n\nWhat are your values about education?  \nComing from a teacher''s perspective :) Education is obviously very important to us. We plan to be very involved in school and make sure our child makes it a priority in their life. I don''t want to pressure them too much seeing as I was a very anxious child when it came to school, but we want them to know that it is important and graduation/ attending college or a trade school is mandatory. It is becoming near impossibly to make a living without a degree in this age and we want to make sure they are prepared. \n\nDo the schools in your area have a good academic reputation – are you planning to have your child in public, private or home school? \nThe schools in our area are excellent. We plan for our child to attend public school. Seeing as I am a teacher, I will have the option to send our child to our districted school or take them to the school where I am teaching. That will all depend on where I am at the time, but regardless we have a definite advantage when it comes to the quality of education. \n\nWill you tell your child about adoption?     If yes, when?  \nYes, I plan to always tell my child about adoption. I have a couple pictures books already. I want them to know how they came to me and what a miracle it all was. I want them to know that they were so loved that two mommies are part of their life. I will always be honest to my child and answer their questions in age appropriate ways. I think secrecy would only lead to a damaged relationship later on. \n\nWhat do envision the future relationship between you and the birth family?\nWe would love to share letters and pictures frequently. We want the birth family to know their child is happy and safe and loved. Visits would be a possibility if we are close enough. \n', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Birth Parent Letter', 5157, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'html', 1372640117, 0),
