(1468, 'I was born in New York as the first grandchild on both sides of my family.  It was a little lonely at first but now I have two loving brothers, the cutest nephew and lots of cousins with children of their own to share with your child. \n\nMy Mom is a nurse and the apple doesn’t fall far from the tree.  She taught me about caring for people, giving back to the community and an appreciation for healthy living and life in general. I have been a physician assistant for over 12 years and enjoy taking care of my patients and always look for ways to improve my community by volunteering. My mom also started a weekly tradition of taking us to the bookstore to chose a book to read for the week.  My love for reading has only grown since then and I look forward to taking your child to the bookstore every weekend for their new book.\n \nMy parents divorced when I was 25 years old and lucky for me, my mom remarried 5 years later to a wonderful man, Stan.  \n\nMy Dad is a retired salesman who was my biggest sideline fan as a child. There wasn''t a softball game, track meet or swim meet that he missed. I think he even enjoyed taking me to Girl Scouts.  I look forward to being your child’s biggest sideline fan in whatever activities they choose. “Pops” is a proud Grandpa and looks forward to another grandchild to love and spoil.\n\nMy “Little” Brothers, Kevin and Kyle are 6 and 8 years younger than me respectively.  During our childhood I was the built in babysitter and looked forward to helping Mom and Dad play Santa at Christmas.  I already have a lot of experience assembling He-Man castles, Matchbox Car tracks and Big Wheels.  As adults we are very close friends and have many things in common such as a love for sports, music and the outdoors.\n\nWhile my parents were at work, I was lucky to spend time with my grandparents and after having the opportunity to live in Germany for over 8 years total as an adult, I now appreciate all the German baking and cooking they tried to teach me. I never realized it was German until living there and understand the importance of preserving my child’s culture and heritage as their life story. I also look forward to passing on the traditions and cultures I have and may even be able to teach your child a little German. Ich spreche ein bisschen Deutsch! (I speak a little German). \n\nWhen I was 8 my family moved to Florida.  There we enjoyed many water activities such as swimming, fishing, boating and later scuba diving.  I participated in competitive swimming as a child through high school and now in adulthood enjoy competing in triathlons. I also volunteer at the local pool with swimming safety classes and look forward to teaching your child to swim like a fish. \n\nAnother love we share as a family is baseball and we look forward to March in Florida and spring training baseball.  Go Braves and Rays! \n\nBoth of my parents instilled in us the desire for learning.  I graduated from the University of Florida with my bachelor’s degree and later from the University of Nebraska with my graduate degree. ', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'My Family and Growing Up', 5194, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'html', 1377898897, 0),
(1469, 'I will raise your child to know their adoption story. Early on, I plan on having open communication with very simple, honest and loving talks. I believe your\nchild needs to know the courage and strength it took for you to make an adoption plan and to give him or her a better life. Our family will celebrate your child’s adoption birthday so your child will be reminded of what a joyous day it was when we welcomed him or her home to our family and be proud of how we found each other and your choice. I will ensure they know their culture and heritage and do everything to preserve this in your child’s life. I will support you in whatever way you are comfortable and will respect your wishes whether you choose a closed or open adoption. It is important to me that you are at peace with your decision. I am humbled that you have taken the time to read my story and are grateful you are considering me as your child’s adoptive mother. Please know that your child will always know the strength and courage it took for you to make an adoption plan and the unconditional love you had to give him or her better life. I will be forever thankful for the blessing you gave to me.\n', '0', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'My Promise to You the Birthmom', 5194, 3, 'non,memb', 1, 0, 'html', 1377899725, 0),
